00:07:44.540 --> 00:07:45.540
also the parsing.

00:07:46.630 --> 00:07:48.800
I think you all changed the rules about the parsing, right?

00:07:48.910 --> 00:07:52.620
One of the pieces of magic of Pydantic is if you had a list

00:07:52.690 --> 00:07:53.740
and you said it was a list of integers,

00:07:53.930 --> 00:07:56.320
but it happened to be strings that could be converted to integers,

00:07:56.530 --> 00:07:57.680
it would just become a list of integers.

00:07:57.870 --> 00:08:00.780
But I feel like you changed the strictness

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:03.720
or looseness of that behavior at one point, right?

00:08:04.380 --> 00:08:06.340
Yeah, we made it a little bit more strict in places.

00:08:06.450 --> 00:08:11.819
We said things like you can't coerce an integer to a string

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:15.260
because basically the original semantics of Pynantic was like,

00:08:15.640 --> 00:08:18.040
we'll just call integer on the thing and see if it's an int.

00:08:19.240 --> 00:08:20.440
And that mostly worked.

00:08:20.540 --> 00:08:22.040
We'll call list on something and see if it's a list.

00:08:22.400 --> 00:08:26.680
Problem is with string, you can call string on everything

00:08:26.900 --> 00:08:27.940
and then you'll get back a string, right?

00:08:28.010 --> 00:08:31.080
So it's no longer a valid test of is it a string to call string on it.

00:08:31.540 --> 00:08:31.960
Right, right.

00:08:32.659 --> 00:08:33.620
What time did this happen?

00:08:33.690 --> 00:08:36.800
It happened at angle bracket class datetime dot datetime dot.

00:08:37.940 --> 00:08:38.680
Yeah, right, exactly.

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:41.800
So yeah, and that's another thing

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:44.920
No one writes their unit tests for the weird edge cases of what's valid.

00:08:45.130 --> 00:08:49.740
But then if you're a bank and one bank is sending you strings for a number or numbers

00:08:49.900 --> 00:08:53.560
for a string and you change it, like we change how it works, that is that's problematic.

