00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:50.060
Tell people just real quickly about Logfire out there.

00:09:50.460 --> 00:09:50.980
Yeah, absolutely.

00:09:50.980 --> 00:09:56.740
So Logfire is an observability platform built, obviously, by the team behind Pydantic.

00:09:57.700 --> 00:10:06.140
If you go to Logfire along the top, I suppose the two things that make it different from some of the stuff that's come before is Logfire is built on open telemetry.

00:10:06.180 --> 00:10:13.560
So on open standards that mean that, yeah, the rails of where the data is being transferred are on an open standard.

00:10:14.250 --> 00:10:21.360
And if you decide you didn't want to use the Logfire platform anymore, you can send that data to anything else that supports OpenTelemetry.

00:10:21.980 --> 00:10:31.700
But unlike lots of other companies in our space, instead of using OpenTelemetry as an excuse to abandon the SDK space and just say, use the horrible OpenTelemetry SDK directly,

00:10:31.830 --> 00:10:35.520
we have the Logfire package, which tries to make that super nice and easy to use.

00:10:36.160 --> 00:10:37.640
And then the other big change we have,

00:10:38.180 --> 00:10:40.700
I think there'll be an example maybe further on down the page,

00:10:40.770 --> 00:10:45.260
but like we, maybe there isn't one right there,

00:10:45.310 --> 00:10:47.540
but we allow you to write SQL directly against your data.

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:48.960
Oh, interesting.

00:10:49.010 --> 00:10:52.300
Instead of having to use kind of click ops to go around and do surveys.

00:10:52.500 --> 00:10:56.640
So if you look here, right, you can go and like write SQL to query your data.

00:10:56.750 --> 00:10:58.880
And so although we're still early,

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:02.960
there are things you can do in Logfire that you cannot

00:11:03.080 --> 00:11:06.120
and have never been able to do in like one of the big incumbents

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:06.960
because it's just SQL.

00:11:07.800 --> 00:11:09.560
And it's obviously much easier to learn for you,

00:11:10.220 --> 00:11:11.540
much easier for LLMs to write.

00:11:11.830 --> 00:11:14.460
So we have the plausible chance in the future

00:11:14.530 --> 00:11:16.900
that you could basically chat with Logfire

00:11:17.020 --> 00:11:18.240
and say, what's wrong with my app?

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:21.220
And the agent can go off and run SQL

00:11:21.460 --> 00:11:24.080
to investigate things in a way that is much harder

00:11:24.110 --> 00:11:25.300
if you have your own dialect.

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:28.080
But to write SQL against data of this scale

00:11:28.340 --> 00:11:30.660
is a monumentally difficult challenge

00:11:31.340 --> 00:11:33.600
and one of the things we struggle with a lot.

00:11:33.630 --> 00:11:36.100
But we think it's useful enough for developers

00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:37.080
that we like put the time in.

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:40.200
- So you can write any SQL you want,

00:11:40.480 --> 00:11:42.460
except for please only do the ones that have indexes.

00:11:43.660 --> 00:11:46.760
- So it's, so our new database is time is data fusion.

00:11:46.980 --> 00:11:48.720
So there were no indexes, but yeah, if you do,

00:11:49.460 --> 00:11:51.920
there are queries you can do now that just like eat memory

00:11:53.560 --> 00:11:55.780
and we have to find ways around them.

00:11:55.790 --> 00:11:57.260
And that's actually the hardest bit is like,

00:11:58.500 --> 00:12:00.000
whether intentionally or not, there are people,

00:12:00.270 --> 00:12:01.760
you know, there are SQL you can write,

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:06.080
which is enormously like heavy to go and compute

00:12:06.100 --> 00:12:12.720
So we have to be able to find ways to process that without taking down other customers, I suppose, is the point.

00:12:12.800 --> 00:12:14.800
You don't want to do a denial of service on yourself.

00:12:15.220 --> 00:12:23.160
Right. I mean, the definition of DOS is that the effort required to DOS is significantly lower than the effort required to process it, right?

00:12:23.300 --> 00:12:25.780
And writing SQL is the ultimate example of that.

00:12:28.180 --> 00:12:29.360
Yeah, it absolutely is.

00:12:29.820 --> 00:12:32.060
- Okay, well that's a really interesting idea

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:33.900
to have SQL there rather than like,

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:37.680
let's just click around our UI until we get an answer

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:38.780
and those sorts of things.

00:12:39.260 --> 00:12:40.740
- Yeah, so I think one of the things,

00:12:41.120 --> 00:12:42.420
we've got some dashboards on that page,

00:12:42.540 --> 00:12:44.500
but the idea is like, sure, we'll go and give you

