before it returns you some representation of that.

00:14:58.960 --> 00:15:04.980
And Jitter came out of this idea that we could do parsing as we do validation.

00:15:05.320 --> 00:15:07.080
So imagine you have a list of integers.

00:15:08.160 --> 00:15:11.220
Instead of what you would traditionally do is you would parse the JSON,

00:15:11.540 --> 00:15:14.100
you would allocate some vector of all of the values in that list,

00:15:14.720 --> 00:15:17.759
each of which would have to be itself a enum of here are the different types

00:15:17.780 --> 00:15:19.700
you might get in JSON because you don't know what it's going to be up front.

00:15:20.500 --> 00:15:23.880
And then once you finish doing that, you can then go and do validation on that.

00:15:24.720 --> 00:15:28.120
And Jitter, the idea is it's an iterative JSON parser, hence the name.

00:15:28.520 --> 00:15:31.940
So you can effectively get, if you think of it in Python parlance,

00:15:31.980 --> 00:15:40.840
it's like an iterable that gives you back each individual element of the JSON as you go along.

00:15:42.120 --> 00:15:47.180
The truth is right now inside Pydantic core, we're still using this JSON value,

00:15:47.380 --> 00:15:50.020
which is Jitter's variant of doing the whole parsing first.

00:15:50.600 --> 00:15:53.380
There are a few optimizations that we get to get away with.

00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:55.840
So there are some really neat things in JSON.

00:15:56.040 --> 00:15:59.020
Like if your strings, for example, John Doe,

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:00.260
you're showing on the screen there,

00:16:01.800 --> 00:16:05.080
does not include any escape sequences like backslash N

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:06.380
or Unicode sequences,

00:16:06.680 --> 00:16:11.540
then you can pass a pointer to that range

00:16:11.560 --> 00:16:13.580
of the underlying JSON object as a string

00:16:13.860 --> 00:16:15.260
instead of having to allocate that string.

00:16:15.460 --> 00:16:18.300
So we do some clever optimizations like that.

